   <h2>Orphanage (<a class="normal" href="http://brea.kfa.st/ak47/004/orphanage" title="View Orphanage">View</a>)</h2>
  <p><a href="/ak47/004/orphanage" title="View Orphanage"><img src="/ak47/004/graphics/004_mk.jpg" alt="Orphanage" title="Orphanage" width="80" height="80" style="float:left; margin-right:5px; margin-bottom:5px;" /></a>I made my first trip to orphanages in late 2000 with Buckner Orphan Care to St. Petersburg, Russia.  I remember watching a broadcast about Romanian orphanages over a decade earlier and I expected to find similar desolate spaces and desperate children.  I was surprised after meeting sweet children who, in spite of, or perhaps, because of, some tough and unfortunate circumstances, exhibited a quiet strength and an understated sense of dignity.  I woke up one morning to a snowy St. Petersburg backdrop and had a long, cathartic cry.  I thought I would come home with predictable photojournalist-type pictures but after being there I had no desire to make those images.  Instead I wanted to make pictures that would dignify the children and give them something back.</p>

<p>This work has been ongoing for over three years and includes work from Russia, Romania, India, Guatemala, and Kenya.  I have tried to avoid images about poverty or pity that are laced with sentimentality.  These images are the polar opposite.  They are about that quiet strength.  It is important to me that the everyday textures and the feel of the rooms is given equal weight - the institution itself speaks as much as the children.</p>

